name: Botany Bay
description: I was going to call this design Botany Bay is something rude followed by something else rude, but I changed my mind in case it negatively affected  any children who came into contact with it. In that way, I am the exact opposite of Botany's authorities who thought nothing of filling its sky with planes and its ocean with tankers. Perhaps I am being unfair. They might have thought something of it. They just decided that they don't really care.

name: Grandfather Christmas
description: I have never understood Christmas. When I was a boy, it was a new thing and nobody was sure what to do with it. A bit like women's rights, I suppose. I gave up on it after my father took me to meet Santa. I thought it had to be a prank, that it was my grandfather playing a silly game. I was wrong. Well, we were all a bit wrong. No-one more so than Santa.

name: Cinematic by Adam Bridgland
description:
It was not easy to convince Delores to accompany me to the beach given she is deaf. It was ten times harder explaining to her why she had to watch me getting arrested later that day. After two hours sat watching the ocean, she turned to me and requested that I say something cinematic. The passing policeman did not deem it necessary to establish why I had screamed "say hello to my little friend" in her face.

www.adambridgland.co.uk

name: Fist by LZP
description:
I recently joined an online dating agency posing as a teenage lesbian. I received 73 date requests, 6 of which were from women. I accepted one request because I liked this, her profile picture. When we met, she was not at all disappointed to learn I am an old man. I think perhaps she expected it. Cynical and talented? That's my kind of woman.

www.louisezpomeroy.com

name: See-Saw-Sam by Millie Hall
description:
I was wearing a suit (another funeral) so I felt confident when I approached her. She stopped sobbing when I said hello. She asked if my name was Darren. I realised she was waiting for a blind date so I said yes. She began wailing. She clambered to her feet and fled. Joke's on her though because Darren arrived 5 minutes later with a bottle of rum, 2 cheeseburgers, a bag of blue pills and a guilty conscience. Friendly chap, Darren. Handy, too, that her name was Sam.

www.milliehall.com.au

name: Shadows
description: I had fled under the cover of darkness to a bar I read about in the newspaper. As I entered, I was confronted by the sight of two man-children (hipsters) making shadow puppets against the wall. They were doing so badly I had to interject. I performed for them the entirety of “The Sunset Limited” in German. When I finished, I rose to my feet, arms outstretched. They didn’t even congratulate me. Perhaps they were right not to; it is an awful play. Then again, maybe they are autistic.

name: Low Cost Airline
description: I told the staff at the home that I was going to Melbourne to see a specialist but I was actually going to see the Cyndi Lauper tour. I travelled with a budget airline so it came as no surprise to find myself seated beside a horse. To break the ice, I asked the horse-lady why she wasn't being transported in a trailer but she did not laugh. Turns out Cyndi was wrong about the horsey ones.

name: Geist by Adam Bridgland
description:
People say you shouldn't mock the afflicted. However, if you are one of the afflicted, then I say it is rude not to. That's why I hide around the home dressed as a ghost. I was having a most excellent time doing it until Maeve became convinced that I was her childhood sweetheart reincarnated. Maeve was clearly quite the goer and sadly never the looker.

www.adambridgland.co.uk

name: Beautiful Redfern
description: I escaped the home for a smoke. I decided to stroll to King's Cross but when I reached Redfern I was exhausted. Disappointed, I collapsed on a nearby bench. I realised then that Redfern is not without charm. The lady on the bench said she did not mind my intrusion and that I could go and visit her in one of these towers. It saved me a fortune in cab fares.

name: Good Advice
description: The lessons we learn as children often hold us back. Take this chap: I saw him looking lost outside a fancy restaurant, phone in hand. I asked him what he was doing. He sighed and said that he was waiting for his dad. I offered him the advice you see here. I hope he went home and changed, but I suspect he just kept trying.  Who taught us to keep trying? Perhaps in this instance it was his father. Perhaps his father is a sadist and more embarrassed than I first reckoned.

name: Happiness by Lutz von Kleinschlang
description: Bill, the man who occupies the room opposite mine, had a visit from his teenage grandson. As they were parting, Bill put his hand on the boy's shoulder and said: "Whatever you do, do it with a smile on your face." When the boy had gone I asked that Bill either refrain from offering advice or that he buy the kid a mask. His teeth looked like a row of derelict council houses.

name: Sweet Idea
description: I will never understand why every idea I propose is not unequivocally accepted. Take this: apparently, this product has no place in the market. Rubbish. No loving parent would buy it for their child. That means two things: tooth decay drops; any kid seen eating them can instantly be identified as neglected. How are they not the best sweets ever?

name: Lest We Remember
description: There is an "Art Therapist" who comes to the home every second Tuesday. The first time she came I thought it was a prank. I suppose she thinks being creative will help us all to come to terms with a past we cannot change and a future we do not have. For our latest session she asked us to make a collage; I threw this in her face as I was leaving.

name: No
description: According to Instagram, my nephew recently took himself to Paris for an underground rave. I like to picture him sauntering down la Champs-Elysee where he spots a young Parisian man in a cafe who tickles his fancy. I imagine him finding the courage to approach and ask, in his best French, if he can join him for a drink. I replay the moment when the boy rejects him. Non, is French for no. I didn’t just forget to add the extra –ce at the end.

name: Uninvited
description: There is a map in the lobby of the home which details the location of all the in-mates' rooms. In case we receive mentally challenged visitors, they have placed a huge sticker that reads “you are here” on the appropriate point on this map. I hate seeing my name on there so I stole this sticker, moved it to where my room can be found, and wrote the word “uninvited” at the bottom. Please never come to see me. You are not welcome.

name: Jeb
description: I arrived at the bus stop to find there was no space for me on the perching bench. I stared at a seated schoolboy until he moved. As he rose, he muttered the word "jeb". I didn't realise I had been insulted until I googled it. I like this word. If he goes before I do, I will smear it on his tombstone in faeces.

name: Nipple
description: Delores, the lady I would like to be intimate with, was reading a magazine in the common room. She looked sad. I approached quietly, so she would not notice me (I don't know why, she is deaf) and observed what had affected her so. It was an advert for perfume. I took it as a sign of her lack and made her a poster in a similar mould. She has yet to smile on my nipple but I did laugh on her forearm.

name: Stacy
description: Roger occupies room number 1 in the home. He enjoys living here. He used to live with his son, but moved out of his own volition when his son took a wife who he despised. Her name, he tells me, is Stacy. I was using the computer room late one night when I came across this. I ordered it for Roger thinking he would find it amusing, however, I cannot say whether I was correct given he has yet to acknowledge it. I checked with the vendor and they say he signed for it himself.

name: Bear and dog
description: I happened upon this sight last Friday as I sat smoking in the park. I have no idea why this man was running around in the rain with no shirt on but he was. Actually, now that I think of it, I could hazard a guess. Either way, I find it to be a rather charming image. The two of them together, that is. Not the shirtless man in the rain.

name: Ham, onion, cheese, egg, mayo.
description: I have eaten the same sandwich for lunch everyday for the last 37 years. I normally supplement it with a side of crisps but I haven’t drawn them here because crisps look a lot like egg yokes when they are screen-printed. I do not have an egg yoke fetish and I would not eat a crisp sandwich if you paid me; I am not a peasant.

name: Peeping Tom by Millie Hall
description: The home has a manager but you wouldn't know it because he never leaves his office. I cannot say why. Perhaps he finds us terrifying. Regardless, I often see him peering at us through the blinds. I hope that I have captured his creepy essence here and that it puts his position under the spotlight. Not because I think he is inept; just because mudslinging is hilarious.

name: Freddy 6 Fingers
description: I once roomed with a man named Friedrich. Friedrich (Freddy) was unremarkable in every way except for the fact that he had six fingers on his right hand. He was always using machinery in the hope that he would lose the extra digit and receive a hefty pay out. Freddy and his unusual tattoo - a tattoo made more unusual by the fact he spoke not a word of English - popped into my head this week as I sharpened my pencil. I wonder what it might have spelled had he been successful.

name: Frenchy
description: Ill Bill’s daughter came with her husband to visit him recently. I listened to the couple as they argued in the hallway. They were fretting about something their little dog had found that should have stayed hidden. Judging by the look of them, this is what I imagine the dog recovered. I cannot say whether it belonged to him or her.

name: Pug
description: The “carers” will not permit smoking inside the home so I am often in the park. I usually enjoy walking there. However, one Friday night I saw this poor animal, lost and alone, and my mood changed; I went from content to delighted in seconds. I whistled as I stepped over him and made my way to the fountain.

name: Dropped one, curled one
description: Maeve is always knitting. I think she does it to compensate for the fact that her life has been a complete waste of time. Andrew, the janitor, joked that she should be careful not to knit herself up into a ball. He followed his statement by winking at me, as if to say it was the funniest thing he has ever said. He is wrong. He once asked me to be careful not to flush tampons down the toilet.

name: Skate for Life
description: I learned recently what a face-plant is. I greatly enjoyed watching a twenty-something year old skater perform one on the steps outside the home. To his credit he didn’t cry. He dusted himself down and muttered: “skate for life.” I admired his resilience so much that I drew what I imagine him to look like if he is good to his word. I originally had him in a wheelchair with shattered knees but I settled in the end for the conservatism of a helmet. Regardless, he is as unemployed in the future as he is now.

name: Wood for the Trees
description: A chipper English fellow joined our ranks yesterday. I have found myself in his room twice already. The first time was to introduce myself. He smiled and said: "very kind but this is a temporary thing. My daughter is going overseas for 73 days and counting. We'll live together when she returns." The second time was to give him this and to welcome him in earnest.

name: Sleeping Beauty
description: I found Bill asleep in the common room with his eyes open. I thought, in that moment, that he was gone. Apparently he just sleeps like that. When he came around, he was delighted to learn that I was mourning. I brought him back to earth by telling him that if he ever does go whilst in our company, we will likely leave him there for 8 hours or so before we realise what has happened.

name: Trolleyed
description: They say every man is an island. If that is the case, I think I met Ibiza one night after hours as I slinked through the park en route back to the home. He looked like me only jaded, high and very homeless. He was staring at one of the many shopping carts they leave lying around this city. I imagine he saw something like this. I was left wondering about life choices and how we end up where we do. I could not decide who between us had triumphed.

name: Secret Service by Millie Hall
description:
After the war, I worked for the German Secret Service. It was a bit like being the guy who has to clear up after a festival. During my second year of spying I made a startling discovery: everyone is boring and everyone is rubbish at life. It basically killed my superego. 

www.milliehall.com.au

name: Paddling Pool
description: From my window, I can see the park. Sadie, the lady responsible for settling newcomers, made a point of telling me how lucky that makes me when she showed me to my room. I dismissed her as simple. However, I had to adjust my opinion when I happened to witness an obese child belly-flop into a paddling pool at an infant’s party. The wave that followed could have carried 5 fleets and by the time it had fallen, the only liquid left in the pool was the salt water of his tears.

William, the chap who lives in the room opposite mine, is convinced we live in a hospice. Perhaps understandably, he is always down. After he rebuffed my efforts to explain the difference between a home and a hospice, I decided the best course of action was to make a joke of it. He didn’t laugh when I showed him this. His granddaughter thought it was hilarious but I suppose 7 year-olds are easily amused.

name: Pool
description: There are instances in my life when I have transgressed and I regret it; there are similar instances that do not trouble me at all. This image portrays both at once. It shows me on holiday in Crete, at the villa of an influential friend, urinating in his pool. Stelios, if you are reading, I am sorry; I am sorry I didn’t do it in your bed. Tax evasion is a crime and even though your pool is delightful, it is certainly not helping me get my hernia operation any quicker.

name: C-gar
description: I have a dream. You may laugh but I am not as gnarled as you might suppose. In my dream, a young lady who I knew when I was a young man at the feet of the snowy Alps, sits in the door well to the home I own – a converted church – smoking my favourite brand of cigar. She stands, approaches me and whispers: “what are you waiting for?” I do not hesitate. I snatch the cigar from her hand and push her backwards into a puddle. I never forgot; I never forget.

name: Good Advice Tote
description: The lessons we learn as children often hold us back. Take this chap: I saw him looking lost outside a fancy restaurant, phone in hand. I asked him what he was doing. He sighed and said that he was waiting for his dad. I offered him the advice you see here. I hope he went home and changed, but I suspect he just kept trying.  Who taught us to keep trying? Perhaps in this instance it was his father. Perhaps his father is a sadist and more embarrassed than I first reckoned.

name: Sumo Suit
description: When I first met Sumo, I thought he was a rat so I tried to destroy him. Maeve barely flinched when she found me chasing her pet down the hall with a hammer in my hand. This came as a pleasant surprise until I realised that she was only calm because she had an excuse to knit Sumo a coat. "This coat", she said, "will make it clear to everyone what Sumo is." I agree; he is a smug rat now and his card is still marked.

name: Gobsh*te tote
description: Back when I used to care, I wrote books. They were never published, probably because they weren't very good. This one I wrote in my 40s. It is loosely based on the autobiography of Keith Urban.

name: Cavalier King Charles Baby Onesie
description: If the adage "people look like their dogs" is true, can you think of any good reason to own a Cavalier King Charles Spaniel? Why draw attention to the fact that you have a face that could haunt houses? Just get a cat. Or a mask. A mask could work.
